Annotation of mobile genetic elements

Query: VariantCaller_final_polish

Produced with bacannot pipeline

04 September 2020

1 About

Mobile genetic elements (MGEs) are a type of genetic materials that can move around within a genome, or that can be transferred from one species or replicon to another. Newly acquired genes through this mechanism can increase fitness by gaining new or additional functions. On the other hand, MGEs can also decrease fitness by introducing disease-causing alleles or mutations. For instance, prophages are bacteriophages that have been inserted and integrated into the bacterial chromosome or plasmid. It is the latent form of a phage. ICEs (integrative and conjugative elements), on the other hand, are integrative mobile genetic elements that encode a conjugation machinery. They can confer selective advantages and can also encode resistance determinants and virulence factors.

In this context, this pipeline automatically annotates prophage sequences and proteins using PHAST database and phigaro software. While ICEberg database is used to annotate ICEs.

About the BLASTs:

  • PHAST is a protein database that contains a vast number of proteins that are commonly found in phages. This database is blasted to the genome via BLASTx and to the predicted genes via BLASTn;
  • ICEberg is a protein and nucleotide database that contains the full-length sequences of known ICEs and also contains the sequences of a multitude of proteins commonly found inside these ICEs. Full-length ICEs are blasted to the genome via BLASTn while the protein sequences are blasted to the genome itself via BLASTx and to the predicted genes via BLASTp.
  • Blast % identity: > 80%
  • Blast % query coverage: > 80%
    • For blasts against gene sequences predicted by Prokka, alignments are filtered in a two way manner so they cover at least 80% of the reference gene sequence and the of query sequence at the same time
    • For blasts against the whole genome, alignments are filtered in a one way manner so they cover at least 80% of only the reference gene sequence
    • Since it is extremely difficult to find an intact full-length ICE in a new genome, these alignments are less stringent and are filtered to have a minimum coverage of 15% of the reference sequence represented in the alignment

The results used to create this report are under the directories called prophages and ICEs in the output folder of the query VariantCaller_final_polish.

2 Genomic Islands prediction

Genomic Islands (GIs) are annotated with islandPath. Its results are all incorporated into JBrowse output and are drawn in yellow. This result shall be seen by using the genome browser provided in the jbrowse directory inside the query main output directory. These genome browser might be opened with JBrowse Desktop sofwtare. Also, a BED file containing the genomic positions of predicted GIs can be found in the predicted_GIs directory under the main output directory.

3 Phigaro prediction

All prophages annotated using phigaro are better shown in its own html report file. The genomic regions predicted as putative prophage sequences are summarized in Table 3.1.

  • Check it out at:

    • HTML: /Volumes/falmeida1TB/bacannot_teste/teste/VariantCaller_final_polish/prophages/phigaro/VariantCaller_final_polish_phigaro.html

It is worthy taking notes of prophage’s genomic regions for a better exploration using the JBROWSE genome browser provided. This genome browser was automatically created (stored in a dir called jbrowse) and can be visualized with JBROWSE desktop.

5 ICEberg database annotation

5.1 Analysis of full-length ICEs

Full-length ICEs are available at ICEberg database in nucleotide fastas while the proteins found inside these ICEs are in protein fastas. The full-length ICEs are very difficult to be completely found in new genomes, thus they are scanned without coverage or identity thresholds. The filtering and selection of these is up to you.

We have found a total of 0 alignments in the query genome, check it out in table 5.1.

Table 5.1: Alignment of full-length ICEs to the query genome via BLASTn

5.2 Analysis of ICE’s proteins

5.2.1 Against the whole genome

All ICE’s proteins from ICEberg database that had good alignments to the query genome (whole genome) are summarised in Table 5.2. We report both annotations using the predicted genes and the whole genome because Prokka uses prodigal to predicted genes which may miss some genomes.

Take note: The fact that the genome possess some proteins from ICEs does not necessarily means that the ICE is present in the genome. Please, check the number of proteins that the ICE of origin posses in the ICEberg database list of ICEs, and them infer based one the alignments you see if your genome have or not one ICE in it.

Table 5.2: ICE genes annotated from ICEberg database via BLASTx

5.2.2 Against the predicted genes

All query genes predicted by Prokka that have a match in ICEberg database are shown in Table 5.3. It is summarised the ICE id and all its genes that were found in the query genome. All of them are linked to the database for further investigations.

Take note: The fact that the genome possess some proteins from ICEs does not necessarily means that the ICE is present in the genome. Please, check the number of proteins that the ICE of origin posses in the ICEberg database list of ICEs, and them infer based one the alignments you see if your genome have or not one ICE in it.

Users are advised to also use the ICEfinder tool to predict genomic position of known ICEs since we are not allowed to include this step under this pipeline.
